                "html": `<h1>Week 10, Day 4: GUI Layout Management - Grid vs. Pack</h1>
<p>Today we learn how to organize widgets <b>professionally</b> using layout managers. This is the difference between a messy interface and a polished application.</p>

<div class="analogy-box">
    <b>Analogy: Furniture Arrangement 🛋️</b><br/>
    <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
        <li><b>Pack()</b> = Stacking boxes in a closet (one after another)</li>
        <li><b>Grid()</b> = Arranging furniture on a grid-based floor plan</li>
        <li><b>Place()</b> = Precise positioning with tape measure (pixel-perfect)</li>
        <li><b>Frames</b> = Rooms within a house (organizing sections)</li>
    </ul>
</div>

<h3>Key Topics</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Pack() geometry manager (simple stacking)</li>
    <li>Grid() geometry manager (table-like layout)</li>
    <li>Place() geometry manager (absolute positioning)</li>
    <li>Using Frames to organize complex layouts</li>
    <li>Padding and widget spacing</li>
    <li>Responsive design considerations</li>
</ul>

<h3>In-Depth Explanation</h3>

<b>a. Pack() Manager - The Simple Stacker</b><br/>

<b>1. Basic Pack() Usage:</b>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre>
        import tkinter as tk
        
        window = tk.Tk()
        window.title("Pack Manager Example")
        
        # Default packing (top to bottom)
        tk.Label(window, text="Label 1", bg="red", width=20).pack()
        tk.Label(window, text="Label 2", bg="green", width=20).pack()
        tk.Label(window, text="Label 3", bg="blue", width=20).pack()
        
        window.mainloop()
    </pre>
    <small>Pack() stacks widgets vertically by default, in the order they're packed.</small>
</div>

<b>2. Pack() Options:</b>
<div style="background-color: #f9f9f9; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px; display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 10px;">
    <div>
        <b>Side options:</b><br/>
        <code>pack(side="top")</code> - Default<br/>
        <code>pack(side="bottom")</code><br/>
        <code>pack(side="left")</code><br/>
        <code>pack(side="right")</code>
    </div>
    <div>
        <b>Padding options:</b><br/>
        <code>pack(padx=10, pady=5)</code><br/>
        <code>pack(ipadx=5, ipady=2)</code><br/>
        <code>pack(fill="x")</code><br/>
        <code>pack(expand=True)</code>
    </div>
</div>

<b>3. Pack() Example with Multiple Sides:</b>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre>
        # Header (top)
        header = tk.Label(window, text="Header", bg="lightgray")
        header.pack(side="top", fill="x", padx=10, pady=5)
        
        # Left sidebar
        sidebar = tk.Label(window, text="Sidebar", bg="lightblue", width=15)
        sidebar.pack(side="left", fill="y", padx=5, pady=5)
        
        # Main content
        content = tk.Label(window, text="Main Content", bg="white")
        content.pack(side="left", expand=True, fill="both", padx=5, pady=5)
        
        # Footer (bottom)
        footer = tk.Label(window, text="Footer", bg="lightgray")
        footer.pack(side="bottom", fill="x", padx=10, pady=5)
    </pre>
</div>

<hr/>

<b>b. Grid() Manager - The Table Organizer</b><br/>

<b>1. Basic Grid() Layout:</b>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre>
        # Create a simple form using grid
        tk.Label(window, text="Username:").grid(row=0, column=0, sticky="e", padx=5, pady=5)
        tk.Entry(window, width=30).grid(row=0, column=1, padx=5, pady=5)
        
        tk.Label(window, text="Password:").grid(row=1, column=0, sticky="e", padx=5, pady=5)
        tk.Entry(window, width=30, show="*").grid(row=1, column=1, padx=5, pady=5)
        
        tk.Button(window, text="Login").grid(row=2, column=1, sticky="e", padx=5, pady=10)
    </pre>
</div>

<b>2. Grid() Options Reference:</b>
<div style="background-color: #f9f9f9; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse;">
        <tr style="background-color: #ddd;">
            <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Option</th>
            <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Description</th>
            <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Example</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><code>row</code>, <code>column</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Cell position (0-based)</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><code>row=0, column=1</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><code>rowspan</code>, <code>columnspan</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Cells to span across</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><code>rowspan=2</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><code>sticky</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Widget alignment (n,s,e,w)</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><code>sticky="nsew"</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><code>padx</code>, <code>pady</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">External padding</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><code>padx=10</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><code>ipadx</code>, <code>ipady</code></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Internal padding</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><code>ipadx=5</code></td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</div>

<b>3. Grid() with Spanning Example:</b>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre>
        # Title spanning all columns
        tk.Label(window, text="Application Form", font=("Arial", 16))\\
              .grid(row=0, column=0, columnspan=3, pady=10)
        
        # Two-column layout
        tk.Label(window, text="First Name:").grid(row=1, column=0, sticky="e", padx=5, pady=5)
        tk.Entry(window).grid(row=1, column=1, padx=5, pady=5)
        
        tk.Label(window, text="Last Name:").grid(row=1, column=2, sticky="e", padx=5, pady=5)
        tk.Entry(window).grid(row=1, column=3, padx=5, pady=5)
        
        # Address (spanning 3 columns)
        tk.Label(window, text="Address:").grid(row=2, column=0, sticky="ne", padx=5, pady=5)
        tk.Text(window, height=4).grid(row=2, column=1, columnspan=3, sticky="nsew", padx=5, pady=5)
        
        # Buttons centered in last row
        tk.Button(window, text="Save").grid(row=3, column=1, pady=10)
        tk.Button(window, text="Cancel").grid(row=3, column=2, pady=10)
    </pre>
</div>

<hr/>

<b>c. Place() Manager - Pixel-Perfect Positioning</b><br/>

<div style="background-color: #ffe6cc; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <b>Warning:</b> Use <code>place()</code> sparingly! It's useful for specific cases but makes responsive design difficult.
</div>

<b>1. Place() Examples:</b>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre>
        # Absolute positioning (pixels)
        tk.Label(window, text="Top-Left", bg="yellow").place(x=10, y=10)
        tk.Label(window, text="Center", bg="lightblue").place(x=200, y=150)
        
        # Relative positioning (% of window)
        tk.Label(window, text="Bottom-Right", bg="lightgreen")\\
              .place(relx=1.0, rely=1.0, anchor="se")
        
        # Overlapping widgets (like tooltips)
        button = tk.Button(window, text="Hover over me")
        button.place(x=100, y=100)
        
        # Tooltip that appears on hover
        tooltip = tk.Label(window, text="This is a tooltip!", bg="white", relief="solid")
        
        def show_tooltip(event):
            tooltip.place(x=event.x_root, y=event.y_root)
        
        button.bind("<Enter>", show_tooltip)
    </pre>
</div>

<hr/>

<b>d. Using Frames - Organizing Complex Layouts</b><br/>

<b>1. Frame-based Layout Structure:</b>
<div style="background-color: #f9f9f9; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre>
        Main Window
        ├── Frame: Header (pack top)
        ├── Frame: Content Area (pack expand)
        │   ├── Frame: Sidebar (grid left)
        │   └── Frame: Main Content (grid right)
        └── Frame: Footer (pack bottom)
    </pre>
</div>

<b>2. Practical Frame Implementation:</b>
<div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre>
        import tkinter as tk
        
        window = tk.Tk()
        window.title("Frame-Based Layout")
        window.geometry("600x400")
        
        # 1. Header Frame (pack top)
        header_frame = tk.Frame(window, bg="lightgray", height=50)
        header_frame.pack(side="top", fill="x")
        tk.Label(header_frame, text="My Application", font=("Arial", 18), bg="lightgray")\\
               .pack(pady=10)
        
        # 2. Content Frame (pack middle, expandable)
        content_frame = tk.Frame(window, bg="white")
        content_frame.pack(side="top", expand=True, fill="both", padx=10, pady=10)
        
        # 2a. Sidebar (grid left)
        sidebar = tk.Frame(content_frame, bg="lightblue", width=150)
        sidebar.grid(row=0, column=0, sticky="ns", padx=(0, 10))
        
        # Sidebar buttons
        buttons = ["Dashboard", "Profile", "Settings", "Help"]
        for i, text in enumerate(buttons):
            tk.Button(sidebar, text=text, width=15)\\
                  .pack(pady=5, padx=10, fill="x")
        
        # 2b. Main Content (grid right, expandable)
        main_content = tk.Frame(content_frame, bg="white", relief="solid", bd=1)
        main_content.grid(row=0, column=1, sticky="nsew")
        
        # Make main_content expand
        content_frame.columnconfigure(1, weight=1)
        content_frame.rowconfigure(0, weight=1)
        
        # Content widgets
        tk.Label(main_content, text="Welcome to the Main Content Area", 
                font=("Arial", 14)).pack(pady=20)
        
        # 3. Footer Frame (pack bottom)
        footer_frame = tk.Frame(window, bg="lightgray", height=30)
        footer_frame.pack(side="bottom", fill="x")
        tk.Label(footer_frame, text="© 2023 My Company", bg="lightgray")\\
               .pack(pady=5)
        
        window.mainloop()
    </pre>
</div>

<hr/>

<b>e. Layout Comparison Table</b>
<div style="background-color: #f9f9f9; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse;">
        <tr style="background-color: #ddd;">
            <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Manager</th>
            <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Best For</th>
            <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Pros</th>
            <th style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Cons</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><b>Pack()</b></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Simple vertical/horizontal layouts</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Easy to use, good for prototypes</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Limited control, not for complex layouts</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><b>Grid()</b></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Forms, tables, complex layouts</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Precise control, professional results</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Learning curve, requires planning</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;"><b>Place()</b></td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Overlays, tooltips, custom drawing</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Pixel-perfect positioning</td>
            <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #aaa;">Not responsive, hard to maintain</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</div>

<hr/>

<h3>Hands-On Exercise: Build a Calculator Layout</h3>
<b>Task:</b> Create the complete GUI layout for a calculator using Grid() manager.<br/><br/>

<b>Requirements:</b>
<div style="background-color: #f0f8ff; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    1. Display screen at top (Entry widget)<br/>
    2. Number buttons 0-9 in grid pattern<br/>
    3. Operator buttons (+, -, ×, ÷, =)<br/>
    4. Additional buttons (C, CE, .)<br/>
    5. Professional spacing and alignment<br/>
    6. Responsive design (buttons expand with window)<br/>
    7. Use frames to group related buttons
</div>

<b>Grid Layout Plan:</b>
<div style="background-color: #f9f9f9; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre style="font-family: monospace;">
        Row 0: [            Display Screen           ] (colspan=4)
        Row 1: [  7  ] [  8  ] [  9  ] [  ÷  ]
        Row 2: [  4  ] [  5  ] [  6  ] [  ×  ]
        Row 3: [  1  ] [  2  ] [  3  ] [  -  ]
        Row 4: [  0  ] [  .  ] [  =  ] [  +  ]
        Row 5: [         C         ] [        CE       ] (colspan=2 each)
    </pre>
</div>

<b>Implementation Steps:</b>
<div style="background-color: #fff0e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <b>Step 1:</b> Create main window and display Entry widget (colspan=4)<br/>
    <b>Step 2:</b> Create number buttons using loops (for rows 1-4)<br/>
    <b>Step 3:</b> Add operator buttons in column 3<br/>
    <b>Step 4:</b> Configure grid weights for expansion<br/>
    <b>Step 5:</b> Add padding and styling<br/>
    <b>Step 6:</b> Test resizing behavior<br/>
    <b>Step 7:</b> Add keyboard bindings (bonus)<br/>
</div>

<hr/>

<h3>Common Layout Mistakes</h3>

<b>Mistake 1: Mixing geometry managers in same container</b>
<div style="background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre>
        # WRONG - Causes Tkinter error!
        label1.pack()
        label2.grid(row=0, column=0)
        
        # RIGHT - Choose one per container
        label1.pack()
        label2.pack()
        
        # OR
        label1.grid(row=0, column=0)
        label2.grid(row=1, column=0)
    </pre>
</div>

<b>Mistake 2: Forgetting to configure grid weights</b>
<div style="background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre>
        # Without this, widgets won't expand!
        window.columnconfigure(0, weight=1)
        window.rowconfigure(0, weight=1)
        
        # Make all columns in a frame expand equally
        for i in range(3):
            frame.columnconfigure(i, weight=1)
    </pre>
</div>

<b>Mistake 3: Not using frames for organization</b>
<div style="background-color: #ffe6e6; padding: 15px; margin: 10px 0; border-radius: 5px;">
    <pre>
        # MESSY - Everything in window
        window.grid_rowconfigure(0, weight=1)  # Header
        window.grid_rowconfigure(1, weight=1)  # Content
        window.grid_rowconfigure(2, weight=1)  # Sidebar???
        
        # ORGANIZED - Use frames!
        header_frame.pack(side="top", fill="x")
        content_frame.pack(expand=True, fill="both")
        sidebar_frame.grid(row=0, column=0, in_=content_frame)
    </pre>
</div>

<hr/>

<div class="assignment-box">
