            "11-1": {
                icon: "fa-bars",
                title: "GUI Menus & Navigation Bars",
                html: `<h1>Week 11, Day 1: Advanced GUI – Menus & Navigation Bars</h1>
    <p>Today we move from simple buttons to <b>professional desktop application navigation</b> using menus and menu bars.</p>

    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: Restaurant Menu 🍽️</b><br/>
        <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <li><b>Menu Bar</b> = The menu book itself</li>
            <li><b>Menu</b> = Sections like Starters, Main Course</li>
            <li><b>Menu Item</b> = Individual food options</li>
            <li><b>Separator</b> = Line between food categories</li>
            <li><b>Shortcut</b> = Ordering your usual without reading</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>What GUI Menus Are</li>
        <li>Menu Bar Structure</li>
        <li>Dropdown Menus</li>
        <li>Menu Commands & Callbacks</li>
        <li>Keyboard Shortcuts</li>
    </ul>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Why Menus Matter</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <ul>
            <li>They make apps look <b>professional</b></li>
            <li>They reduce clutter (fewer buttons)</li>
            <li>They follow <b>desktop OS standards</b></li>
            <li>Users already understand them</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Menu Structure (Visual Diagram)</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; border-radius:5px; font-family:monospace;">
        Window<br/>
        └── Menu Bar<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;├── File<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│&nbsp;&nbsp;├── New<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│&nbsp;&nbsp;├── Open<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│&nbsp;&nbsp;├── Save<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│&nbsp;&nbsp;└── Exit<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;├── Edit<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│&nbsp;&nbsp;├── Cut<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│&nbsp;&nbsp;├── Copy<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;│&nbsp;&nbsp;└── Paste<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── Help<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── About
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Creating a Menu Bar (Tkinter)</h3>

    <b>Step 1: Create the Main Window</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
import tkinter as tk

root = tk.Tk()
root.title("Inventory Manager")
root.geometry("600x400")
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Step 2: Create the Menu Bar</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
menu_bar = tk.Menu(root)
root.config(menu=menu_bar)
        </pre>
        <small>- Menu bar must be attached to the window</small>
    </div>

    <b>Step 3: Create a Dropdown Menu</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
file_menu = tk.Menu(menu_bar, tearoff=0)
menu_bar.add_cascade(label="File", menu=file_menu)
        </pre>
        <small>- <code>tearoff=0</code> disables floating menus</small>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Adding Menu Items (Commands)</h3>

    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
def new_file():
    print("New file created")

def exit_app():
    root.quit()

file_menu.add_command(label="New", command=new_file)
file_menu.add_separator()
file_menu.add_command(label="Exit", command=exit_app)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Rule:</b>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;">
        Menu items always trigger <b>functions</b>, never direct code.
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Keyboard Shortcuts (Accelerators)</h3>

    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
file_menu.add_command(
    label="Save",
    accelerator="Ctrl+S",
    command=lambda: print("Saved")
)

root.bind("&lt;Control-s&gt;", lambda e: print("Saved"))
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Shortcut Mapping Table</b>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <table border="1" cellpadding="8" cellspacing="0">
            <tr>
                <th>Shortcut</th>
                <th>Binding</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Ctrl + S</td>
                <td>&lt;Control-s&gt;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Ctrl + N</td>
                <td>&lt;Control-n&gt;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Ctrl + Q</td>
                <td>&lt;Control-q&gt;</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Multiple Menus Example</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
edit_menu = tk.Menu(menu_bar, tearoff=0)
menu_bar.add_cascade(label="Edit", menu=edit_menu)

edit_menu.add_command(label="Cut")
edit_menu.add_command(label="Copy")
edit_menu.add_command(label="Paste")
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Common Menu Design Standards</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <ul>
            <li><b>File</b> → New, Open, Save, Exit</li>
            <li><b>Edit</b> → Cut, Copy, Paste</li>
            <li><b>View</b> → Zoom, Layout</li>
            <li><b>Help</b> → About</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Hands-On Exercise: Build an App Menu</h3>
    <b>Task:</b> Add a professional menu to your Warehouse Manager app.

    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <b>Requirements:</b><br/>
        1. Menu bar at top<br/>
        2. File menu with New, Save, Exit<br/>
        3. Edit menu with Cut, Copy, Paste<br/>
        4. Help menu with About popup (placeholder)<br/>
        5. At least one keyboard shortcut
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Common Mistakes</h3>

    <b>Mistake 1: Forgetting to attach menu to window</b>
    <div style="background-color:#ffe6e6; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
menu = tk.Menu()
# Won't appear unless attached to root
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Mistake 2: Writing logic directly in menu</b>
    <div style="background-color:#ffe6e6; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
# WRONG
add_command(label="Exit", command=root.quit())
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="assignment-box">
        <h4>Assignment</h4>
        <p>Create a fully working menu system for your app.</p>

        <ul>
            <li>Menus must trigger functions</li>
            <li>Use at least one separator</li>
            <li>Include one shortcut key</li>
            <li>Test menu responsiveness</li>
        </ul>

        <p><b>Bonus:</b> Disable a menu item dynamically using <code>entryconfig</code>.</p>
    </div>`
            },
            "11-2": {
                icon: "fa-comment-dots",
                title: "Pop-ups & Message Boxes",
                html: `<h1>Week 11, Day 2: Advanced GUI – Pop-ups & Message Boxes</h1>
    <p>Today we learn how applications <b>communicate with users</b> using pop-ups: alerts, confirmations, warnings, and input dialogs.</p>

    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: Phone Notifications 📱</b><br/>
        <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <li><b>Info Box</b> = WhatsApp message received</li>
            <li><b>Warning Box</b> = Low battery alert</li>
            <li><b>Error Box</b> = App crash message</li>
            <li><b>Confirm Box</b> = “Are you sure you want to delete?”</li>
            <li><b>Input Dialog</b> = Enter your PIN</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Why Pop-ups Matter</li>
        <li>Message Box Types</li>
        <li>Handling User Responses</li>
        <li>Custom Dialog Windows</li>
        <li>Real-world GUI Scenarios</li>
    </ul>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Why Pop-ups Are Important</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <ul>
            <li>Guide user decisions</li>
            <li>Prevent destructive actions</li>
            <li>Display errors clearly</li>
            <li>Collect quick user input</li>
            <li>Improve usability & trust</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Types of Message Boxes</h3>

    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <table border="1" cellpadding="8" cellspacing="0">
            <tr>
                <th>Type</th>
                <th>Purpose</th>
                <th>Example</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>showinfo</td>
                <td>General information</td>
                <td>“Item saved successfully”</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>showwarning</td>
                <td>Potential issue</td>
                <td>“Low stock warning”</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>showerror</td>
                <td>Critical problem</td>
                <td>“Failed to save file”</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>askyesno</td>
                <td>Confirmation</td>
                <td>“Delete this item?”</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>askokcancel</td>
                <td>Confirm / cancel</td>
                <td>“Proceed with changes?”</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Using Message Boxes in Tkinter</h3>

    <b>Step 1: Import Messagebox</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
from tkinter import messagebox
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Step 2: Information Pop-up</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
messagebox.showinfo(
    "Success",
    "Item added successfully!"
)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Step 3: Warning Pop-up</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
messagebox.showwarning(
    "Low Stock",
    "Only 2 items left in inventory!"
)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Step 4: Error Pop-up</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
messagebox.showerror(
    "Error",
    "Failed to connect to database"
)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Confirmation Dialogs (User Decision)</h3>

    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
response = messagebox.askyesno(
    "Confirm Delete",
    "Are you sure you want to delete this item?"
)

if response:
    print("Item deleted")
else:
    print("Action cancelled")
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Important:</b>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;">
        Confirmation dialogs always return <b>True or False</b>.
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Dialog Flow Diagram</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; border-radius:5px; font-family:monospace;">
        User clicks button<br/>
        └── Show popup<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;├── User confirms → Execute action<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── User cancels → Do nothing
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Input Dialogs (Getting User Data)</h3>

    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
from tkinter.simpledialog import askstring

name = askstring(
    "Item Name",
    "Enter product name:"
)

if name:
    print("Product:", name)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Use Cases:</b>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;">
        - Rename items<br/>
        - Enter passwords<br/>
        - Quick data capture
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Custom Pop-up Windows</h3>
    <p>Sometimes built-in dialogs are not enough. We create custom pop-ups using <code>Toplevel</code>.</p>

    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
popup = tk.Toplevel(root)
popup.title("About App")
popup.geometry("300x150")

tk.Label(popup, text="Warehouse Manager v1.0").pack(pady=10)
tk.Button(popup, text="Close", command=popup.destroy).pack()
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Difference Table</b>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <table border="1" cellpadding="8">
            <tr>
                <th>Messagebox</th>
                <th>Custom Popup</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Quick & simple</td>
                <td>Fully customizable</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Limited design</td>
                <td>Custom layout & widgets</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>One purpose</td>
                <td>Complex workflows</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Hands-On Exercise: Inventory Alerts</h3>
    <b>Task:</b> Add pop-up logic to your Warehouse Manager.

    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <b>Requirements:</b><br/>
        1. Show success popup when item is added<br/>
        2. Show warning if stock &lt; 5<br/>
        3. Confirm before deleting item<br/>
        4. Show error if input is empty<br/>
        5. Add an About popup window
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Common Mistakes</h3>

    <b>Mistake 1: Ignoring user response</b>
    <div style="background-color:#ffe6e6; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
messagebox.askyesno("Delete", "Sure?")
# Response not stored → useless
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Mistake 2: Blocking logic confusion</b>
    <div style="background-color:#ffe6e6; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        Messageboxes pause code execution until user responds.
    </div>

    <b>Mistake 3: Overusing pop-ups</b>
    <div style="background-color:#ffe6e6; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        Too many pop-ups frustrate users. Use only when necessary.
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="assignment-box">
        <h4>Assignment</h4>
        <p>Upgrade your app using smart pop-ups.</p>

        <ul>
            <li>At least 3 different popup types</li>
            <li>One confirmation dialog</li>
            <li>One custom popup window</li>
            <li>Clean user flow (no spam)</li>
        </ul>

        <p><b>Bonus:</b> Disable buttons unless confirmation is accepted.</p>
    </div>`
            },
            "11-3": {
                icon: "fa-paint-brush",
                title: "Canvas & Images",
                html: `<h1>Week 11, Day 3: Advanced GUI – Canvas & Images</h1>
    <p>Today we learn how to <b>draw, visualize, and display images</b> inside GUI applications using the Canvas widget.</p>

    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: Whiteboard 🖊️</b><br/>
        <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <li><b>Canvas</b> = The whiteboard</li>
            <li><b>Shapes</b> = Drawings on the board</li>
            <li><b>Images</b> = Stickers placed on the board</li>
            <li><b>Coordinates</b> = Where you draw</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>What Canvas Is</li>
        <li>Canvas Coordinates System</li>
        <li>Drawing Shapes</li>
        <li>Displaying Images</li>
        <li>Practical Visual Use Cases</li>
    </ul>

    <hr/>

    <h3>What Is a Canvas?</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <p>A Canvas is a <b>free drawing surface</b> where you can:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Draw shapes</li>
            <li>Place images</li>
            <li>Create charts</li>
            <li>Build custom UI elements</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Canvas Coordinate System</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; border-radius:5px; font-family:monospace;">
        (0,0) ─────────────▶ X<br/>
          │<br/>
          │<br/>
          ▼<br/>
          Y
    </div>

    <small>Top-left corner is (0,0)</small>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Creating a Canvas</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
canvas = tk.Canvas(
    root,
    width=400,
    height=300,
    bg="white"
)
canvas.pack()
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Drawing Shapes</h3>

    <b>Rectangle</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
canvas.create_rectangle(
    50, 50, 200, 150,
    fill="lightblue",
    outline="black"
)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Circle (Oval)</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
canvas.create_oval(
    100, 100, 200, 200,
    fill="lightgreen"
)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Line</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
canvas.create_line(
    0, 0, 300, 200,
    fill="red",
    width=3
)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Canvas Shape Summary</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <table border="1" cellpadding="8">
            <tr>
                <th>Method</th>
                <th>Purpose</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>create_rectangle</td>
                <td>Boxes, cards</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>create_oval</td>
                <td>Circles, indicators</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>create_line</td>
                <td>Graphs, dividers</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>create_text</td>
                <td>Custom labels</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Displaying Images</h3>

    <div style="background-color:#ffe6e6; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <b>Important Rule:</b> Image objects must be stored in a variable, or they disappear!
    </div>

    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
from PIL import Image, ImageTk

img = Image.open("logo.png")
img = img.resize((100, 100))
photo = ImageTk.PhotoImage(img)

canvas.create_image(
    200, 150,
    image=photo
)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Real-World Uses</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <ul>
            <li>App logos</li>
            <li>Charts & dashboards</li>
            <li>Drawing tools</li>
            <li>Game boards</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Hands-On Exercise</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <b>Task:</b> Build a dashboard canvas<br/><br/>
        1. Draw a header rectangle<br/>
        2. Add an app logo image<br/>
        3. Draw 3 status circles (green/yellow/red)<br/>
        4. Add text labels
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="assignment-box">
        <h4>Assignment</h4>
        <p>Create a visual dashboard using Canvas.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>At least 3 shapes</li>
            <li>At least 1 image</li>
            <li>Use correct coordinates</li>
        </ul>
        <p><b>Bonus:</b> Change colors dynamically.</p>
    </div>`
            },
            "11-4": {
                icon: "fa-keyboard",
                title: "Keyboard Bindings & Shortcuts",
                html: `<h1>Week 11, Day 4: Advanced GUI – Keyboard Bindings & Shortcuts</h1>
    <p>Today we turn our app into a <b>power-user tool</b> by controlling it with the keyboard.</p>

    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: Video Games 🎮</b><br/>
        <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <li><b>Mouse</b> = Casual player</li>
            <li><b>Keyboard</b> = Pro player</li>
            <li><b>Shortcuts</b> = Special moves</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Key Events</li>
        <li>Binding Keys</li>
        <li>Keyboard Shortcuts</li>
        <li>Event Objects</li>
        <li>Accessibility Benefits</li>
    </ul>

    <hr/>

    <h3>What Is Key Binding?</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <p>Key binding allows your app to <b>listen and react</b> to keyboard input.</p>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Binding a Key</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
def say_hello(event):
    print("Hello!")

root.bind("&lt;h&gt;", say_hello)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <small>Pressing <b>H</b> triggers the function.</small>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Special Keys</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <table border="1" cellpadding="8">
            <tr>
                <th>Key</th>
                <th>Binding</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Enter</td>
                <td>&lt;Return&gt;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Escape</td>
                <td>&lt;Escape&gt;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Arrow Up</td>
                <td>&lt;Up&gt;</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Arrow Down</td>
                <td>&lt;Down&gt;</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Shortcut Keys (Ctrl / Alt)</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
root.bind("&lt;Control-s&gt;", lambda e: print("Saved"))
root.bind("&lt;Control-q&gt;", lambda e: root.quit())
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Understanding the Event Object</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
def key_info(event):
    print("Key:", event.keysym)
    print("Key code:", event.keycode)

root.bind("&lt;Key&gt;", key_info)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Event Flow Diagram</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; font-family:monospace;">
        Key Pressed<br/>
        └── Event Created<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── Bound Function Executes
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Practical Examples</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px;">
        <ul>
            <li>Enter key submits a form</li>
            <li>Esc closes popup</li>
            <li>Ctrl+S saves data</li>
            <li>Arrow keys navigate lists</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Hands-On Exercise</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px;">
        <b>Task:</b> Add keyboard control to your app<br/><br/>
        1. Ctrl+S → Save<br/>
        2. Ctrl+Q → Exit<br/>
        3. Enter → Submit form<br/>
        4. Esc → Close popup
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Common Mistakes</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#ffe6e6; padding:15px;">
        <ul>
            <li>Forgetting the <code>event</code> parameter</li>
            <li>Binding keys to the wrong widget</li>
            <li>Overlapping shortcuts</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="assignment-box">
        <h4>Week 11 Final Assignment</h4>
        <p>Upgrade your app to be keyboard-friendly.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>At least 4 shortcuts</li>
            <li>One popup closed by Esc</li>
            <li>One form submitted by Enter</li>
        </ul>
        <p><b>Bonus:</b> Display pressed key names on screen.</p>
    </div>`
            },

            "12-1": {
                icon: "fa-database",
                title: "Connecting GUI Apps to SQLite",
                html: `<h1>Week 12, Day 1: Database Integration – Connecting to SQLite</h1>
    <p>Today we move from temporary data to <b>permanent storage</b> by connecting our GUI application to a database.</p>

    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: Notebook vs Filing Cabinet 🗄️</b><br/>
        <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <li><b>Variables</b> = Writing on a whiteboard (lost later)</li>
            <li><b>Files (.txt)</b> = A notebook</li>
            <li><b>Database</b> = A filing cabinet with labeled drawers</li>
            <li><b>Tables</b> = Drawers</li>
            <li><b>Rows</b> = Individual files</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>What a Database Is</li>
        <li>Why SQLite</li>
        <li>Database Structure</li>
        <li>Connecting Python to SQLite</li>
        <li>Creating a Database File</li>
    </ul>

    <hr/>

    <h3>What Is a Database?</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <p>A database is a <b>structured storage system</b> that:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Saves data permanently</li>
            <li>Organizes data logically</li>
            <li>Allows fast searching & updating</li>
            <li>Works even after app closes</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Why SQLite?</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <table border="1" cellpadding="8">
            <tr>
                <th>SQLite</th>
                <th>MySQL / PostgreSQL</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>No installation needed</td>
                <td>Requires server setup</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Single file (.db)</td>
                <td>Multiple system files</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Perfect for desktop apps</td>
                <td>Better for web apps</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Database Structure (Visual)</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; font-family:monospace; border-radius:5px;">
        Database (warehouse.db)<br/>
        └── products table<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;├── id (INTEGER)<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;├── name (TEXT)<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;├── price (REAL)<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── quantity (INTEGER)
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Connecting to SQLite</h3>

    <b>Step 1: Import SQLite</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
import sqlite3
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Step 2: Create / Connect to Database</b>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
connection = sqlite3.connect("warehouse.db")
cursor = connection.cursor()
        </pre>
        <small>- If file doesn’t exist, SQLite creates it automatically</small>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Creating a Table</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <pre>
cursor.execute("""
CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS products (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    name TEXT NOT NULL,
    price REAL,
    quantity INTEGER
)
""")

connection.commit()
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Important Rules:</b>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:10px; border-radius:5px;">
        - Tables must be created before inserting data<br/>
        - Always commit changes<br/>
        - Use IF NOT EXISTS to avoid crashes
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>SQLite Data Types</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; border-radius:5px;">
        <table border="1" cellpadding="8">
            <tr>
                <th>Type</th>
                <th>Use</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>INTEGER</td>
                <td>Whole numbers</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>REAL</td>
                <td>Decimals</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>TEXT</td>
                <td>Strings</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>BLOB</td>
                <td>Images / files</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>GUI + Database Flow</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; font-family:monospace;">
        User enters data<br/>
        └── Clicks Save<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── Python validates input<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── SQLite saves record
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Hands-On Exercise: Database Setup</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px;">
        <b>Task:</b> Prepare your app for database usage<br/><br/>
        1. Create a database file<br/>
        2. Create a products table<br/>
        3. Ensure table persists after app restart<br/>
        4. Print confirmation message
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Common Mistakes</h3>

    <div style="background-color:#ffe6e6; padding:15px;">
        <ul>
            <li>Forgetting <code>commit()</code></li>
            <li>Closing connection too early</li>
            <li>Misspelling column names</li>
            <li>Recreating tables every run</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="assignment-box">
        <h4>Assignment</h4>
        <p>Integrate SQLite into your GUI app.</p>

        <ul>
            <li>Create a <code>.db</code> file</li>
            <li>Create at least one table</li>
            <li>Connect from Python successfully</li>
            <li>Explain table structure in comments</li>
        </ul>

        <p><b>Bonus:</b> Display database file size in console.</p>
    </div>`
            },
            "12-2": {
                icon: "fa-table",
                title: "Executing SQL Commands (CRUD)",
                html: `<h1>Week 12, Day 2: Database Integration – SQL Commands (CRUD)</h1>
    <p>Today we learn how to <b>create, read, update, and delete</b> data in a database from our GUI app.</p>

    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: School Register 📒</b><br/>
        <ul style="margin-top: 10px;">
            <li><b>Create</b> = Add a new student</li>
            <li><b>Read</b> = Check attendance list</li>
            <li><b>Update</b> = Correct a student’s name</li>
            <li><b>Delete</b> = Remove a student</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>What CRUD Means</li>
        <li>INSERT statements</li>
        <li>SELECT queries</li>
        <li>UPDATE records</li>
        <li>DELETE safely</li>
    </ul>

    <hr/>

    <h3>CRUD Overview</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px;">
        <table border="1" cellpadding="8">
            <tr>
                <th>Operation</th>
                <th>SQL Command</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Create</td>
                <td>INSERT</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Read</td>
                <td>SELECT</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Update</td>
                <td>UPDATE</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Delete</td>
                <td>DELETE</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>INSERT – Adding Data</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px;">
        <pre>
cursor.execute(
    "INSERT INTO products (name, price, quantity) VALUES (?, ?, ?)",
    ("Laptop", 2500, 5)
)
connection.commit()
        </pre>
    </div>

    <b>Why use ? placeholders?</b>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:10px;">
        Prevents SQL Injection and syntax errors.
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>SELECT – Reading Data</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px;">
        <pre>
cursor.execute("SELECT * FROM products")
rows = cursor.fetchall()

for row in rows:
    print(row)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>UPDATE – Modifying Data</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px;">
        <pre>
cursor.execute(
    "UPDATE products SET quantity = ? WHERE id = ?",
    (10, 1)
)
connection.commit()
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>DELETE – Removing Data</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px;">
        <pre>
cursor.execute(
    "DELETE FROM products WHERE id = ?",
    (1,)
)
connection.commit()
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>SQL Execution Flow</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; font-family:monospace;">
        User action<br/>
        └── SQL query prepared<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── Executed via cursor<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── Commit saves changes
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Hands-On Exercise</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px;">
        <b>Task:</b><br/>
        1. Insert 3 products<br/>
        2. Display all products<br/>
        3. Update quantity of one product<br/>
        4. Delete one product
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Common Mistakes</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#ffe6e6; padding:15px;">
        <ul>
            <li>Forgetting WHERE clause (updates everything!)</li>
            <li>Not committing changes</li>
            <li>Using string formatting instead of placeholders</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="assignment-box">
        <h4>Assignment</h4>
        <p>Implement full CRUD operations.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Use placeholders</li>
            <li>Show data in console</li>
            <li>Handle missing records</li>
        </ul>
    </div>`
            },
            "12-3": {
                icon: "fa-list",
                title: "Displaying Records in GUI Tables",
                html: `<h1>Week 12, Day 3: Database Integration – Displaying Records</h1>
    <p>Today we display database records inside the GUI using tables.</p>

    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: Excel Spreadsheet 📊</b><br/>
        Rows = records<br/>
        Columns = fields
    </div>

    <h3>Key Topics</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Why tables matter</li>
        <li>Treeview widget</li>
        <li>Populating tables</li>
        <li>Refreshing data</li>
    </ul>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Treeview Widget</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f0f8ff; padding:15px;">
        <p><code>Treeview</code> displays structured data like a spreadsheet.</p>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Creating a Table</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px;">
        <pre>
from tkinter import ttk

table = ttk.Treeview(
    root,
    columns=("Name", "Price", "Qty"),
    show="headings"
)

table.heading("Name", text="Name")
table.heading("Price", text="Price")
table.heading("Qty", text="Quantity")

table.pack(fill="both", expand=True)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Loading Data from Database</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px;">
        <pre>
cursor.execute("SELECT name, price, quantity FROM products")
rows = cursor.fetchall()

for row in rows:
    table.insert("", "end", values=row)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>Refreshing the Table</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#e0e0e0; padding:15px;">
        <pre>
for item in table.get_children():
    table.delete(item)
        </pre>
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <h3>GUI + DB Flow</h3>
    <div style="background-color:#f9f9f9; padding:15px; font-family:monospace;">
        Database<br/>
        └── SELECT query<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── Data fetched<br/>
        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;└── Inserted into table
    </div>

    <hr/>

    <div class="assignment-box">
        <h4>Assignment</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Display all products in a table</li>
            <li>Auto-refresh after insert</li>
            <li>Proper column labels</li>
        </ul>
        <p><b>Bonus:</b> Enable row selection.</p>
    </div>`
            },
            "12-4": {
                icon: "fa-search",
                title: "Building a Search Feature",
                html: `<h1>Week 12, Day 4: Database Integration – Search Functionality</h1>
    <p>Today we make our app <b>smart and user-friendly</b> by adding search.</p>

    <div class="analogy-box">
        <b>Analogy: Google 🔍</b><br/>
